comment:
Canada is politically different from the UK and yanks in several ways, so foreign spying and hacking won't be the same.  Potentially, more difficult to do.

 First, there are three viable parties that could form a ruling government, and minority governments are common.  A majority can't dictate when there is no majority.

Second, provincial and federal parties may have the same name, but they function separately.  The four liberal party premiers (out of 13 governments) DON'T answer to Trudeau.

Third, elections Canada still keeps a paper trail.  If computers were hacked and data stolen or destroyed, we could still have a free, dair and trustworthy election.

Fourth, we still use paper ballots marked with pencils.  "E ballot" fraud is impossible.  When votes are counted, representatives of all parties are there to ensure there's no fraud.  And the paper kept in case recounts are necessary.

Because of out first-past-the-post voting system. The share of the popular vote is not usually the same as the share of seats in Parliament.

In 2015, Trudeau campaigned on changing this to a more fair system, then changed his mind when he won. This year's election is exactly why: under a fair system, the Liberals wouldn't have done so well. They have a vested interest in keeping first-past-the-post.

Ummm this article is not super accurate.  First off, Trudeau did not perssure JWR to drop the charges against SNC, she was asked to consider a deferred prosecution agreement, or DPA, where the company would face large fines instead of criminal prosecution.  Execs at SNC were threatening to pull out of QC, potentially costing thousands their jobs.  2nd, it has come to light that JWR acted a bit unethically in her position by recording other people without their knowledge during calls (a no no in Canada) and irregulairties in travel expense claims.  She was shifted to another cabinet position, which she resigned from in protest, and was then expelled from the party.  She just wasn't very good at her job, and became a very devisive figure.  The commision stated that Trudeau commited an ethics violation, which results in a fine, and JWR herself has stated that no criminal laws were broken.

Trans Mountain is def an issue, but it's an issue thanks to our previous PM, Stephen Harper.  Long story short, he signed an agreement with China, and if the pipeline doesn't get built, Canada has to pay a fine to the tune of 150 million bucks.  Trudeau is, I believe, taking climate change seriously, and he's trying to enact change, and is doing a good job so far.  He's our first PM to take concrete steps into addressing it.

Blackface.  Not great but the pictures were from one school event 20 years ago, where he dressed up as Aladdin.  He owned up to the pics, apologized, and it was pretty much a non issue after that, except for the Conservatives.  Also the india thing.
